WEBVTT

00:01.625 --> 00:03.291
[Meredith] <i>We surgeons</i>
<i>have come up with a stitch</i>

00:03.375 --> 00:05.291
<i>for just about anything.</i>

00:05.375 --> 00:08.041
<i>Get a mole removed-- </i><i>subcutaneous suture.</i>

00:08.125 --> 00:11.709
<i>Snag your arm on barbed wire--</i>
<i>loose interrupted suture.</i>

00:11.792 --> 00:13.875
<i>Internal bleed-- silk.</i>

00:13.959 --> 00:17.000
<i>Slice your scalp open...</i>
<i>well, </i><i>that's gonna need staples.</i>

00:17.083 --> 00:18.959
I heard you got into an OR today.

00:19.041 --> 00:20.250
<i>♪ I'll end up strange</i>
<i>If I don't go crazy first ♪</i>

00:20.333 --> 00:22.208
I'm jealous. I haven't
held a scalpel in two weeks.

00:22.291 --> 00:23.875
[Jackson] Yeah, well,
if it's any consolation,

00:23.959 --> 00:26.083
it was 98 degrees in full PPE.

00:27.000 --> 00:29.667
Debriding a poor kid's burns
from a wildfire.

00:29.750 --> 00:31.166
All I do is run codes.

00:31.250 --> 00:34.834
I get a break when I get to get
a family in to say goodbye,

00:34.917 --> 00:36.709
and then I just run another code.

00:36.792 --> 00:38.917
Yeah, well, you're not gonna
like this part, then.

00:39.000 --> 00:40.875
<i>♪ I shoulda known wouldn't heal me ♪</i>

00:40.959 --> 00:42.125
I'm not even done yet.

00:42.208 --> 00:44.166
<i>♪ And I'm finding some peace ♪</i>

00:44.375 --> 00:49.250
[Meredith] <i>We obsess about making every</i>
<i>stitch precise and strong.</i>

00:49.333 --> 00:50.291
[siren wailing]

00:50.375 --> 00:52.625
<i>♪ Life goes on ♪</i>

00:52.709 --> 00:53.834
You asleep?

00:55.041 --> 00:57.000
<i>♪ No free will without the choice ♪</i>

00:57.542 --> 01:00.083
Thanks, Grey.
I was perfectly content in that dream.

01:00.166 --> 01:01.959
<i>♪ I can't think around the noise ♪</i>

01:02.750 --> 01:03.834
Where were you?

01:03.917 --> 01:06.458
[groans] I was in a field

01:06.542 --> 01:08.041
near where I grew up in Ireland.

01:08.166 --> 01:10.041
But instead of barley,

01:10.125 --> 01:11.375
it was just dead bodies.

01:11.458 --> 01:12.834
-And you want to go back there?
-[cellphone chimes]

01:13.792 --> 01:15.959
I want to go anywhere
that isn't this bloody place.

01:18.667 --> 01:19.875
Back to it.

01:20.542 --> 01:23.208
-Your mask is--
-Falling apart? Yeah.

01:23.291 --> 01:26.542
I gave my new one for today
to one of the nurses. [chuckles softly]

01:26.625 --> 01:28.041
<i>♪ Life goes on ♪</i>

01:32.208 --> 01:34.250
[woman, over PA]
<i>Dr. Mannard to radiology.</i>

01:34.333 --> 01:35.458
<i>Dr. Mannard to radiology.</i>

01:35.542 --> 01:37.166
[Maggie] Richard. Hey!

01:37.250 --> 01:39.458
-Is everything OK?
-Uh, yeah, yeah.

01:39.542 --> 01:42.959
I'm just going over patients',
um, uh, supply needs...

01:43.041 --> 01:44.166
-Oh.
-...with, um--

01:44.250 --> 01:45.834
Ready for you, Dr. Pierce.

01:45.917 --> 01:47.333
[elevator bell dings]

01:47.417 --> 01:48.583
With Dr. Fox.

01:51.041 --> 01:55.041
Uh, I'll just, uh, take the stairs.

01:57.291 --> 01:58.709
[Catherine] Go easy on that hip.

01:58.792 --> 02:01.333
You don't want to get hurt
on your first day back.

02:01.417 --> 02:03.000
Well, thanks.

02:03.083 --> 02:06.250
But the only pain I'm feeling
right now is square in my ass.

02:07.792 --> 02:09.041
[huffs]

02:23.166 --> 02:24.709
[Bailey shudders, groans]

02:24.792 --> 02:27.000
I swear, if that idiot broke my nose,

02:27.083 --> 02:29.000
-I swear I'm gonna sue--
-[Bailey] Sir, shut up!

02:29.083 --> 02:33.041
Uh, DeLuca, here.
Take the other father over to bed 7.

02:33.125 --> 02:35.041
If it's occupied,
I don't care where he goes,

02:35.125 --> 02:36.500
as long as he's
15 yards away from that one.

02:36.583 --> 02:37.834
OK. You got it, Chief.

02:37.917 --> 02:40.291
-[sighs]
-[Levi] There's tissue swelling,

02:40.375 --> 02:41.542
she had trouble putting weight on it,

02:41.917 --> 02:43.417
and I can see some slight bruising.

02:43.500 --> 02:45.959
It's probably a sprain,
but I ordered an X-ray to be safe.

02:46.041 --> 02:46.917
[Nico] What happened, exactly?

02:47.000 --> 02:49.375
I rolled it or someone stomped on it.

02:49.458 --> 02:51.458
I-I don't-- I don't know.
It happened fast.

02:51.542 --> 02:53.333
All right, well,
it's most likely just a sprain,

02:53.417 --> 02:55.542
but, Schmitt, shout when you get an X-ray.
I'll take a look.

02:56.750 --> 02:58.375
[groans]

02:58.458 --> 03:00.083
[Levi] Chief, that's exactly what I said.

03:00.166 --> 03:01.834
But you're not the orthopedic surgeon.

03:01.917 --> 03:03.166
Come on. Radiology! Let's go.

03:03.250 --> 03:04.458
[sighs]

03:12.166 --> 03:15.125
Bailey needs soccer or T-ball.

03:15.208 --> 03:17.375
Or maybe we could get him
to run wind sprints

03:17.458 --> 03:19.041
up and down the driveway
just to wear him out.

03:19.125 --> 03:20.583
You think that would be cruel?

03:20.709 --> 03:21.709
[sighs]

03:21.792 --> 03:23.417
What's with everybody
posting "Happy birthday"

03:23.500 --> 03:26.667
all over your social media?
Your birthday's next week.

03:26.959 --> 03:28.458
[sighs]

03:28.542 --> 03:30.583
Wait. No.

03:30.667 --> 03:31.542
I didn't miss--

03:32.959 --> 03:34.875
How is next week already over?

03:34.959 --> 03:37.500
I missed it myself until my mom called.

03:37.583 --> 03:39.625
[sighs] Our lives are insane.

03:40.417 --> 03:42.917
OK, but when your mom called,
why didn't you tell me?

03:44.500 --> 03:46.750
-I didn't want you to feel bad.
-[sighs]

03:46.834 --> 03:48.625
I feel bad <i>now!</i>

03:48.709 --> 03:49.750
[sighs]

03:49.834 --> 03:51.417
I'm hungry.

03:52.667 --> 03:55.125
[sighs] Babe, I-I'm not upset.

03:55.208 --> 03:56.959
I promise. I-I ju--

03:57.041 --> 03:58.375
I lived another year.

03:58.750 --> 04:01.125
I made a healthy baby
with a woman I am crazy about.

04:02.500 --> 04:03.792
[sighs] It's all good.

04:03.875 --> 04:05.250
Oh, God.

04:06.208 --> 04:07.583
[tape rewinds]

04:08.583 --> 04:10.417
You are the cutest, Scout.

04:10.500 --> 04:12.709
Or maybe not Scout.

04:13.375 --> 04:14.375
Why not Scout?

04:14.500 --> 04:15.834
I'm not sure yet.

04:15.917 --> 04:18.000
Oh. Why not Scout?

04:19.083 --> 04:21.166
I love Scout as a nickname,

04:21.375 --> 04:22.500
and I love you.

04:22.583 --> 04:24.041
I got that. I'm good.

04:24.125 --> 04:26.000
But we should name him.

04:26.291 --> 04:27.417
I agree with Link.

04:27.500 --> 04:28.667
-On Scout?
-On naming him.

04:28.750 --> 04:29.959
What about Tony?

04:30.583 --> 04:31.792
-Mm...
-You hate it.

04:32.125 --> 04:33.542
-Tony Soprano.
-[Link] "Tony Baloney."

04:33.625 --> 04:34.792
"Tony's a phony."

04:36.083 --> 04:37.709
I'm allowed to not like names, right?

04:37.792 --> 04:39.375
I'm not weighing in on that.

04:41.750 --> 04:44.417
Now... he's adorable,
whatever his name is.

04:44.500 --> 04:45.375
Right.

04:45.959 --> 04:48.959
Except... not Tony.

04:51.125 --> 04:53.041
No, not Tony.

04:53.166 --> 04:55.625
Thank you, sir.
Please wait over there. Next!

04:56.458 --> 04:58.709
[siren wails in distance]

04:58.792 --> 05:01.375
-Hey.
-Hey. Sorry to pull you from screening,

05:01.458 --> 05:02.834
but we're running low
on doctors over here.

05:02.917 --> 05:04.834
This should be the last kid
from the wildfire.

05:04.917 --> 05:06.083
Nice change of pace--

05:06.166 --> 05:08.709
I mean... not nice.

05:08.792 --> 05:11.083
Obviously, it's-- it's terrible
and infuriating,

05:11.166 --> 05:13.166
and, you know,
for the first time in my career,

05:13.250 --> 05:15.667
I haven't seen a stroke
or a heart attack within a week,

05:15.750 --> 05:17.500
and I know that people
are still having them,

05:17.583 --> 05:19.250
but they're just afraid
to come in because of COVID,

05:19.333 --> 05:20.667
which means they're dying at home.

05:22.000 --> 05:25.291
[sighs] Sorry. Not a lot of opportunity
to vent these days.

05:26.000 --> 05:27.875
[siren wailing in distance]

05:27.959 --> 05:30.709
Listen, Teddy, I know we've
barely spoken since, um...

05:30.792 --> 05:32.667
You don't-- You don't need to say it.

05:33.083 --> 05:34.500
But I've been thinking, and...

05:35.875 --> 05:37.083
there are some things we should talk about

05:37.166 --> 05:39.250
[sighs] maybe after work,

05:39.333 --> 05:41.917
-if our schedules allow?
-Yes, yes, yeah.

05:42.000 --> 05:43.542
Let's-- Let's-- Let's talk.

05:43.625 --> 05:44.750
[siren chirps]

05:49.083 --> 05:49.959
[sighs]

05:51.333 --> 05:52.333
[paramedic] 18-year-old male

05:52.458 --> 05:54.750
found half a mile
from the Black Ball Hill fire.

05:54.834 --> 05:57.667
Penetrating abdominal trauma
from a broken tree shard.

05:57.834 --> 05:59.291
Otherwise, alert and oriented times three.

05:59.458 --> 06:00.834
Let's get him to trauma 2. Let's go.

06:00.917 --> 06:02.333
Please don't tell my dad.

06:02.417 --> 06:04.125
[tape rewinds]

06:09.041 --> 06:10.125
Hey.

06:10.208 --> 06:12.041
Amelia and Link had their baby.

06:12.125 --> 06:14.500
Did you see him? Really cute little guy.

06:14.583 --> 06:16.917
-What happened last night?
-Oh, my mom told you, right?

06:17.000 --> 06:19.000
I, uh, had a last-minute
emergency surgery.

06:19.083 --> 06:20.083
I should have texted,

06:20.333 --> 06:22.250
or a voicemail would have worked, too.

06:22.333 --> 06:23.417
[chuckles]

06:24.208 --> 06:26.000
To tell me that our wedding was off?

06:26.709 --> 06:28.959
What? Not off, just-- just delayed.

06:29.041 --> 06:30.834
Why would it be off?

06:31.750 --> 06:34.458
I don't know. I don't know.
I just-- I-I guess I-I--

06:34.542 --> 06:37.834
I-It just-- I kind of-- I got thrown.

06:37.917 --> 06:41.291
Yeah. OK. Well, got it.

06:41.375 --> 06:44.166
Well, no. No. I don't want
to cancel our wedding, Teddy.

06:44.792 --> 06:47.125
-Do you?
-No. [sighs]

06:47.208 --> 06:49.041
[cellphone vibrates, chimes]

06:49.125 --> 06:51.750
[sighs] Trauma's coming in.
See ya.

07:00.250 --> 07:04.166
[chuckles] Would you like me
to buy you a Porsche, as well?

07:04.250 --> 07:05.667
Maybe a private jet?

07:05.750 --> 07:06.959
I know it looks like a lot--

07:07.041 --> 07:09.208
It doesn't look like a lot. It <i>is </i>a lot!

07:09.291 --> 07:10.625
It is unreasonable.

07:10.709 --> 07:13.083
Catherine, it is just what I need

07:13.166 --> 07:16.333
to keep my patients alive and safe.

07:16.417 --> 07:17.417
What is unreasonable

07:17.500 --> 07:19.333
is that too many of them
are Black and Brown,

07:19.417 --> 07:20.500
and not enough people seem to care.

07:20.583 --> 07:22.625
-I know that!
-Then why are you yelling at me?

07:23.041 --> 07:23.959
I'm not yelling at you,

07:24.041 --> 07:25.834
I'm yelling at the world through you!

07:25.917 --> 07:27.542
I hate this.

07:27.667 --> 07:29.709
I hate this!

07:29.875 --> 07:31.250
I am good at my job,

07:31.458 --> 07:33.625
and I have yet to meet a problem
that I couldn't fix

07:33.709 --> 07:35.041
until this!

07:36.542 --> 07:39.041
Try it, Maggie! It feels good to yell.

07:40.125 --> 07:41.458
I hate this, too!

07:41.542 --> 07:43.500
-Yeah!
-I hate this!

07:43.792 --> 07:46.250
I hate that I've had to cancel
all of my surgeries!

07:46.333 --> 07:48.041
I hate that people are dying

07:48.125 --> 07:50.583
because they don't have access
to healthcare!

07:50.667 --> 07:54.458
I hate that my entire day
is spent on a computer conference!

07:54.542 --> 07:55.500
Conference, conference!

07:55.583 --> 07:59.417
And I hate that everyone
is dying no matter what we do!

07:59.500 --> 08:01.583
Lord, I hate that everyone is dying!

08:01.667 --> 08:02.792
I hate that I can't fix it!

08:02.875 --> 08:04.750
I hate that I can't fix this!

08:04.959 --> 08:07.041
[both screaming]

08:07.125 --> 08:10.333
[both laughing]

08:14.166 --> 08:15.250
[groans]

08:15.333 --> 08:19.917
And I hate that my husband
hasn't come back to me.

08:20.000 --> 08:21.458
[sighs]

08:23.667 --> 08:25.917
[groans]

08:26.000 --> 08:27.291
I hate that, too.

08:31.208 --> 08:32.291
[sighs]

08:33.875 --> 08:36.250
[elevator bell dings]

08:36.333 --> 08:38.542
[Koracick] Hey.
[clears throat] Dr. Webber?

08:38.625 --> 08:42.250
Uh, I-I heard about
your PPE cleaning hack.

08:42.333 --> 08:43.458
Smart. [chuckles]

08:43.542 --> 08:44.834
Well, I'm glad to help.

08:44.917 --> 08:46.250
I-I-- You know, I've been meaning to ask,

08:46.333 --> 08:49.208
how are things, uh, with you and Dr. Fox?

08:51.375 --> 08:54.083
You want to know
if she's back on the market?

08:54.625 --> 08:55.917
How kind of you to offer. No.

08:56.000 --> 09:00.542
I-I wondered if I could, uh,
take credit for your idea.

09:00.625 --> 09:01.500
Buy a little goodwill.

09:03.291 --> 09:05.250
Yeah, forget it. I'll just, uh--

09:05.333 --> 09:07.000
I'll just hide from her instead.

09:11.417 --> 09:13.208
[tape rewinds]

09:14.583 --> 09:17.125
[Richard] <i>We cannot blame, um,</i>

09:17.208 --> 09:20.667
<i>environment, toxins, </i><i>family history.</i>

09:20.750 --> 09:22.500
How 'bout that last quarter, huh?

09:22.583 --> 09:25.542
<i>Cells need apologies,</i>

09:25.625 --> 09:27.583
<i>-and they need to know </i><i>on an elemental--</i>
-No, no, no. No, no, no.

09:27.667 --> 09:29.834
The conference confirmed that
they weren't gonna post this.

09:29.917 --> 09:31.667
-Damn it!
-[groans] They didn't.

09:31.750 --> 09:33.625
It was someone's cellphone.

09:33.709 --> 09:35.000
I've gone viral.

09:35.083 --> 09:36.542
All right. That's fine.
We issue a press release.

09:36.625 --> 09:38.625
We explain the whole thing.
We explain the symptoms

09:38.709 --> 09:40.333
and the dangers of cobalt poisoning.

09:40.417 --> 09:41.333
People need to know the risks.

09:41.417 --> 09:45.667
My reputation, Jackson--
It's everything I had.

09:45.834 --> 09:47.250
And it's still intact, all right?

09:47.333 --> 09:50.041
You have a legendary career. You got sick.

09:50.125 --> 09:53.417
It's tempting to want to point
to my illness and say,

09:53.500 --> 09:55.750
"That's why he made so many mistakes."

09:55.834 --> 09:58.834
But rigorous honesty
is a tenet of my sobriety,

09:58.917 --> 10:00.834
and if I look at myself in the mirror,

10:00.917 --> 10:04.208
I know there were things
that were not the cobalt.

10:04.291 --> 10:05.583
They were just me.

10:05.667 --> 10:07.417
Look, I told Maggie

10:07.542 --> 10:09.208
she should operate on her cousin.

10:09.375 --> 10:10.834
That was a tough call.
In that circumstance,

10:10.917 --> 10:12.208
I might have made the same decision.

10:12.500 --> 10:15.166
And I spent time with a woman
who wasn't your mother.

10:16.500 --> 10:18.959
I knew it was wrong, and I did it anyway,

10:19.750 --> 10:22.959
all because she... puffed up my ego.

10:23.625 --> 10:25.583
It wasn't physical. I made sure of that.

10:26.166 --> 10:27.375
But, still, it--

10:28.792 --> 10:30.125
it felt like cheating.

10:31.667 --> 10:34.000
And I have no one to blame but myself.

10:34.083 --> 10:35.333
[cellphone chimes]

10:36.625 --> 10:37.750
Ah, my patient.

10:37.875 --> 10:40.750
Ah, you-- you go.

10:48.709 --> 10:52.458
[indistinct talking on television]

10:52.542 --> 10:55.959
School is done, and the kids
are watching a movie.

10:56.750 --> 10:59.583
All three of them? How'd you swing that?

10:59.959 --> 11:02.500
I told them it's what you wanted
for your re-birthday.

11:02.583 --> 11:06.667
[sighs] I missed the real one,
so now it's today. Surprise!

11:06.750 --> 11:08.417
Amelia, you don't have to...

11:08.500 --> 11:10.750
Do you realize what I have done?

11:11.667 --> 11:14.083
When was the last time
every child in this house

11:14.166 --> 11:17.083
was doing something
that did not involve us?

11:17.166 --> 11:18.375
And the baby's asleep.

11:18.458 --> 11:20.166
The baby has a name.

11:25.041 --> 11:27.834
But... I just forgot it.

11:27.959 --> 11:29.834
[television continues]

11:29.917 --> 11:31.834
[baby cooing]

11:31.917 --> 11:33.291
[Link] Mikey.

11:33.375 --> 11:35.291
[baby cooing]

11:35.375 --> 11:36.250
Evan.

11:38.417 --> 11:39.375
Toby.

11:40.250 --> 11:41.125
What are you doing?

11:41.750 --> 11:43.875
Oh, uh, I figured

11:43.959 --> 11:46.083
if we couldn't pick a name,

11:46.792 --> 11:48.166
he could pick his own.

11:48.250 --> 11:51.250
Maybe he'll react
when I say the right one.

11:51.709 --> 11:54.542
Hmm? And I can't think of a better idea.

11:55.583 --> 11:56.458
Mark.

11:57.125 --> 11:59.375
[laughs]

11:59.458 --> 12:00.333
Gabriel.

12:00.417 --> 12:01.834
No, no, no, not that one.

12:02.542 --> 12:04.417
-Gabe Lincoln?
-Oh, God.

12:05.625 --> 12:06.959
Maybe we should try some girl names.

12:07.041 --> 12:08.667
We don't know if he'll identify as male.

12:08.750 --> 12:09.625
Good point.

12:10.208 --> 12:11.166
Kimberly.

12:14.083 --> 12:16.542
[monitor beeping]

12:17.500 --> 12:20.500
This kid's dad attacked another kid's dad,

12:20.583 --> 12:22.458
somehow Bailey's foot got involved,

12:22.542 --> 12:24.000
and now they're all in the ER.

12:24.291 --> 12:28.250
Well, I'm OK with that as long
as no one's dying of the plague.

12:28.333 --> 12:30.625
DeLuca's wondering if there's
an update for the dad.

12:31.291 --> 12:33.291
I mean, his blood pressure's
barely holding,

12:33.375 --> 12:36.917
and his burns are extensive,
so it's a long road.

12:38.458 --> 12:39.500
Oh, wow.

12:41.250 --> 12:44.000
These burns have gone through
the muscle, into his chest?

12:44.083 --> 12:45.333
Wait, you're touching his lung?

12:45.417 --> 12:46.709
Have cardio meet us in the OR.

12:46.792 --> 12:48.083
Get a thoracotomy tray ready right away.

12:48.166 --> 12:49.291
I'm on it.

12:51.333 --> 12:53.500
[siren wailing in distance]

13:05.458 --> 13:07.667
[sighs, sniffs]

13:07.750 --> 13:09.500
-Hey.
-Hey.

13:09.667 --> 13:11.792
Look, I-I don't know
when I'm gonna get another quiet moment,

13:11.875 --> 13:13.208
so do you want to talk now?

13:13.291 --> 13:15.667
Uh, yeah, sure. That's a good idea.

13:15.750 --> 13:17.792
There hasn't really been
much time to think lately.

13:17.875 --> 13:19.917
But what little time
there has been, I've been--

13:21.667 --> 13:22.959
I've been thinking about the future

13:24.208 --> 13:25.375
and <i>our </i>future.

13:26.125 --> 13:27.250
Yeah, me, too.

13:29.166 --> 13:31.667
So I took a look at my medical
directives and my will.

13:32.834 --> 13:35.709
And if anything happened to me,

13:35.792 --> 13:37.166
obviously, you'd get Allison,

13:37.250 --> 13:38.959
uh, but we haven't made a plan for Leo.

13:39.041 --> 13:40.208
-[clears throat]
-Owen, I want to talk about us.

13:40.291 --> 13:42.291
And I haven't talked to Amelia
and Link about this...

13:42.375 --> 13:43.875
I wanna talk about you and me.

13:43.959 --> 13:45.542
...but if you-- if you can't,
then maybe they'd be willing--

13:45.625 --> 13:47.041
[cellphone vibrates, chimes]

13:47.125 --> 13:49.041
-At least then, the kids would--
-[cellphone vibrates, chimes]

13:49.125 --> 13:50.291
You-- You need to get that?

13:50.583 --> 13:51.959
Yeah. I-I'm sorry. I, um--

13:52.041 --> 13:55.041
Um, yeah. The OR needs me now.

13:55.250 --> 13:56.375
Yeah. OK.

13:56.458 --> 13:59.333
Owen, look. Leo and Allison,
they're brother and sister.

13:59.417 --> 14:01.125
I w-- I-I don't want to split them up.

14:01.208 --> 14:02.375
Of course not. I don't, either.

14:02.458 --> 14:03.667
And if you're OK with them both--

14:03.750 --> 14:06.959
[scoffs] I'm not OK
with you dying, Owen.

14:09.875 --> 14:11.291
Let's talk later, then.

14:18.458 --> 14:21.125
[Meredith] Hey, hey, Hayes!
I got your page.

14:21.208 --> 14:23.458
-Please tell me it's a surgery.
-It's surgery.

14:23.542 --> 14:25.375
Oh, good, 'cause I can't
call time of death

14:25.458 --> 14:26.917
on one more person.

14:27.000 --> 14:28.750
And I don't want it
to be someone's grandmother.

14:28.834 --> 14:30.834
Oh, you'd prefer it was a teenager?

14:30.917 --> 14:32.834
Well, no, no. That came out wrong.

14:32.917 --> 14:34.166
I just want to do what I'm best at,

14:34.250 --> 14:35.792
and cutting people open
is what I'm best at,

14:35.875 --> 14:37.709
-and what do we have?
-Frankie Morris.

14:37.792 --> 14:40.125
Eight weeks ago, I helped
give him a transplanted kidney

14:40.208 --> 14:41.542
for ARPKD.

14:41.625 --> 14:43.041
It was behaving beautifully

14:43.125 --> 14:45.166
till a tree branch
penetrated it earlier today.

14:45.458 --> 14:47.000
Injured the superior pole.

14:47.083 --> 14:48.917
-Tree branch?
-He was running from a wildfire.

14:49.000 --> 14:51.500
-What do you think?
-I think I'm saving a kidney!

14:54.875 --> 14:56.166
-You coming?
-Well, I wouldn't mind,

14:56.250 --> 14:57.792
considering it's my patient.

14:58.250 --> 14:59.667
Stay out of my way.

14:59.750 --> 15:00.834
Uh-huh.

15:03.166 --> 15:04.208
[Levi] How does this feel?

15:04.291 --> 15:06.166
T-T-- It feels like
you put on a tourniquet,

15:06.250 --> 15:08.667
and all my blood flow has stopped. T-- Ah!

15:08.750 --> 15:12.709
All right. Uh, we got some soft
tissue swelling but no fracture.

15:12.875 --> 15:14.792
You'll be as good as new
in a few days if you stay off it.

15:15.083 --> 15:16.750
-Oh.
-Great. Just like I thought.

15:17.750 --> 15:19.291
[sighs]

15:20.041 --> 15:21.458
[Richard] Ah.

15:21.542 --> 15:22.583
Well, what happened here?

15:22.667 --> 15:25.792
There was a fistfight
between some parents.

15:25.875 --> 15:26.917
You start it?

15:27.583 --> 15:29.041
I live in a hotel.

15:29.125 --> 15:31.166
My sister-in-law takes care of my boys.

15:31.250 --> 15:32.375
I only get to see my husband

15:32.458 --> 15:35.417
when he comes here
to clap for me every 12 hours,

15:35.542 --> 15:38.375
and two grown men just used me
as a wrestling mat.

15:38.458 --> 15:40.125
-You're not funny.
-[knock on door]

15:40.208 --> 15:41.583
Dr. Fox is ready for you, Chief.

15:41.750 --> 15:42.917
-Ugh.
-Ohh.

15:42.959 --> 15:44.375
Should I tell her to wait?

15:44.542 --> 15:46.917
And if so, can someone else?
Because I am not her favorite.

15:47.083 --> 15:49.125
-[Levi] So conference room?
-[sighs]

15:49.208 --> 15:51.333
No. Cancun.

15:52.166 --> 15:53.709
See? That was funny.

15:53.792 --> 15:54.709
Chief Bailey?

15:54.792 --> 15:56.875
T-- Uh, tell her I'll be there soon.

15:59.208 --> 16:01.041
Ugh.

16:03.417 --> 16:05.250
[Jackson] <i>Rigorous honesty, right?</i>

16:05.333 --> 16:08.959
I am here to be
rigorously honest with you.

16:09.041 --> 16:10.542
No, not right now, thank you.

16:10.625 --> 16:11.792
I'm gonna tell you my truth,
and you're gonna listen,

16:11.875 --> 16:13.875
whether you like it or not,
because you're bed-bound

16:13.959 --> 16:15.083
and I'm not.

16:17.333 --> 16:19.375
I know it's really hard
to live with my mom.

16:20.417 --> 16:21.750
I know she can be withholding

16:21.834 --> 16:24.083
when she's angry or feels slighted.

16:25.542 --> 16:27.250
And I remember.
I know she didn't say anything

16:27.333 --> 16:28.750
when Bailey fired you.

16:29.375 --> 16:30.750
I have been where you are.

16:30.834 --> 16:32.917
I get it. And, yeah, I'm a little pissed

16:33.000 --> 16:34.709
about the whole other-woman thing,

16:34.792 --> 16:36.250
but you know what? A-At my core,

16:36.333 --> 16:38.000
I kind of-- I kind of even get that, too,

16:38.083 --> 16:40.834
because I know that Mom
can push people to need to prove

16:40.917 --> 16:43.458
that she is not the sun, moon,
and stars all rolled into one,

16:43.542 --> 16:45.000
to prove that you're your own man,

16:45.083 --> 16:47.333
to prove that, "Hey, sometimes
you're just plain wrong,"

16:47.417 --> 16:48.542
even if she'll never admit it.

16:48.625 --> 16:50.250
I also get that she kind of <i>is</i>

16:50.333 --> 16:51.959
the sun, moon, and stars
all rolled into one,

16:52.041 --> 16:53.583
especially when she loves you,

16:53.667 --> 16:57.291
'cause when she loves you,
man, she will move mountains

16:57.375 --> 16:58.333
to help you.

16:58.458 --> 17:01.125
She will dedicate herself
totally and completely

17:01.208 --> 17:03.458
to helping you, to getting you
where you need to go,

17:03.542 --> 17:05.792
however you need to get there.

17:06.417 --> 17:08.125
When she loves, it's super hard.

17:08.208 --> 17:11.166
and all of that love--
it's worth the rest of it.

17:11.250 --> 17:12.667
I know you love her. I know you do.

17:12.750 --> 17:13.834
'Cause you're physically better.

17:13.917 --> 17:16.083
The cobalt's pretty much
out of your system by now.

17:16.166 --> 17:17.625
You're still not yourself.
You're not even fighting

17:17.709 --> 17:19.709
for your damn reputation
or your career, Richard,

17:19.792 --> 17:21.834
'cause your wife isn't here.

17:21.917 --> 17:23.625
Why is that? 'Cause you sent her away.

17:24.750 --> 17:26.041
I know with all of my being

17:26.125 --> 17:29.208
that you need to get over this
stubborn ego, stubborn pride,

17:29.333 --> 17:31.625
and go call and claim
the woman that you love,

17:31.709 --> 17:32.667
'cause you're not gonna get over it.

17:33.250 --> 17:35.083
And you're damn sure
never gonna get over her.

17:37.375 --> 17:39.333
You know, I'm not too old
to kick your ass.

17:39.417 --> 17:40.583
[chuckles]

17:44.041 --> 17:45.542
I always wanted a son.

17:45.625 --> 17:47.166
Well, you've got one.

17:47.834 --> 17:51.125
So when she calls you,
just answer the damn phone, OK?

17:51.208 --> 17:52.500
Hear her out.

17:52.583 --> 17:54.208
If you don't want to do it
for yourself, do it for me.

17:55.458 --> 17:56.750
[monitors beeping]

17:56.834 --> 17:59.000
[Jackson] Can I get another
two units of blood on standby?

18:00.417 --> 18:01.291
[Teddy and Maggie]
Got your page.

18:01.375 --> 18:03.041
-[Jackson] Get in here.
-Both of you.

18:03.125 --> 18:04.667
His burns have gone past the chest wall

18:04.750 --> 18:06.291
all the way into the thoracic cavity.

18:06.375 --> 18:08.083
[Maggie] Full-thickness burns
all the way to the lungs?

18:08.166 --> 18:09.291
Have you ever seen anything like that?

18:09.375 --> 18:12.208
[Teddy] Yeah, in a bombing in Iraq.

18:12.291 --> 18:13.291
[Jo] Clamp.

18:24.667 --> 18:25.875
[Link] This feels like...

18:27.709 --> 18:28.542
[chuckles]

18:30.417 --> 18:32.917
I had this friend
in the bike shop in Venice.

18:33.000 --> 18:34.041
Mm-hmm.

18:34.750 --> 18:36.750
And one year, it rained like crazy.

18:38.709 --> 18:40.834
And he said, uh,

18:40.917 --> 18:42.709
there had to be this one moment

18:42.792 --> 18:46.333
when all the windshield wipers
on all the cars in the city

18:46.417 --> 18:50.375
were aligned and in sync
just for one or two wipes.

18:51.291 --> 18:56.709
He called it a fleeting moment
of profound harmony.

18:56.792 --> 18:59.667
Mm. This friend smoke a lot of pot?

18:59.750 --> 19:03.500
Mm. Yeah, he had a medical card
<i>and </i>a dealer.

19:04.750 --> 19:07.166
[baby crying over monitor]

19:08.125 --> 19:10.000
-[groans]
-I got it.

19:10.083 --> 19:11.959
You enjoy

19:12.041 --> 19:16.166
your profound moment of fleeting--

19:16.250 --> 19:17.667
Happy birthday. [sighs]

19:17.750 --> 19:18.917
-[chuckles
-[sighs]

19:19.000 --> 19:21.125
[continues crying]

19:25.208 --> 19:26.709
[sighs]

19:26.792 --> 19:29.959
This website says some people
pick names from a dream.

19:30.500 --> 19:32.500
What was the last dream you had
before the baby was born?

19:32.583 --> 19:34.542
Um, does it have to be my dream?

19:34.625 --> 19:37.709
Yes, because I don't think
we should call him

19:37.792 --> 19:39.208
Sex with His Dad.

19:40.166 --> 19:42.500
I don't think Snake in a Vest
is much better.

19:42.583 --> 19:43.750
Right.

19:43.834 --> 19:45.041
OK. Let's keep going.

19:45.125 --> 19:46.750
Power through it. Think outside the box.

19:46.834 --> 19:48.542
No wrong answers.
Say some things you love.

19:48.625 --> 19:52.834
Or we could just take a step back...

19:52.917 --> 19:56.125
rest our brains,
revisit the subject when we feel more...

19:57.500 --> 19:58.709
like ourselves?

19:59.291 --> 20:02.709
"Like ourselves" as in
"not hormonal and crazy"?

20:02.792 --> 20:03.667
I mean...

20:05.417 --> 20:06.959
-Yes?
-Go away.

20:07.041 --> 20:08.250
-I-I--
-Get out

20:08.333 --> 20:09.709
before I shoot breast milk in your eyes.

20:11.959 --> 20:14.041
[suction gurgling, monitor beeping]

20:14.125 --> 20:17.000
[Hayes] No one would be able tell
you've been out of the OR for a while.

20:17.083 --> 20:18.625
I recite surgical steps

20:18.709 --> 20:21.000
when I'm putting on my PPE.

20:21.083 --> 20:23.583
I'm claustrophobic, so it calms me down.

20:24.709 --> 20:25.875
How are your lot taking it?

20:25.959 --> 20:27.166
-My kids?
-Mm-hmm.

20:27.250 --> 20:28.583
Well, I haven't been home in two weeks,

20:28.667 --> 20:31.959
so I'm not sure they remember who I am.

20:32.041 --> 20:33.542
My lads are crawling the walls.

20:33.625 --> 20:35.792
I just pray to God they don't
do anything this stupid.

20:35.875 --> 20:37.125
[Meredith]
Gonna tell me when you were this age,

20:37.208 --> 20:39.417
you don't remember being away
from your friends for two days

20:39.500 --> 20:41.083
feeling like an eternity?

20:41.166 --> 20:42.875
Friends, no. Girlfriend, maybe.

20:42.959 --> 20:44.709
I once hoisted myself
over an electric fence

20:44.792 --> 20:45.667
to get to a girlfriend.

20:47.125 --> 20:48.750
What were you doing
behind an electric fence?

20:48.875 --> 20:50.875
Ah, we don't know each other
well enough for that story yet.

20:53.500 --> 20:55.917
All right, Frankie. Moment of truth.

20:56.083 --> 20:57.709
[Meredith]
We'll have to inspect the calyces,

20:57.917 --> 20:59.333
but so far, so good.

21:03.458 --> 21:05.667
Well, what do you know?
Maybe there is another tomorrow.

21:05.750 --> 21:06.750
[chuckles]

21:06.834 --> 21:08.458
[monitors beeping rapidly]

21:08.542 --> 21:09.792
-Damn it.
-Clamp.

21:12.250 --> 21:13.417
Come on, Frankie.

21:13.667 --> 21:14.583
Come on, Frankie.

21:17.333 --> 21:18.834
No, no, no. Ma, Ma,
you got to do the thing

21:18.917 --> 21:20.083
where you pretend that the broccoli

21:20.166 --> 21:22.417
is the brother of the carrots
that he already ate

21:22.500 --> 21:25.250
and that they need to be
reunited in his tummy.

21:25.333 --> 21:29.250
Yeah, like, uh,
"Please, Mr. Leo. Please, please,

21:29.333 --> 21:31.875
let me be reunited
with my sister in your tummy."

21:31.959 --> 21:35.208
OK? OK, good. Yeah, Ma.
I got to go. I love you. Bye.

21:35.291 --> 21:37.291
[Aaron] Excuse me, Doctor.
Uh, my son is Frankie.

21:37.375 --> 21:38.333
Is there any update?

21:39.250 --> 21:40.500
Do they have to take his new kidney out?

21:40.750 --> 21:41.959
Are-- Are we going through this
all over again?

21:42.041 --> 21:43.417
Well, he only just went up to the O.R.,

21:43.500 --> 21:46.625
so it's gonna be a while
before we know, I'm afraid.

21:48.500 --> 21:51.333
You know, when COVID started,
I told Frankie, "Now it's our turn

21:51.417 --> 21:54.250
to protect the doctors
and nurses who helped you,"

21:54.333 --> 21:56.083
and we have been diligent and careful.

21:56.166 --> 21:57.917
We have quarantined, and we have prayed,

21:57.959 --> 22:02.083
and now my own son, my son who is alive

22:02.166 --> 22:05.041
because a good person died
and donated a kidney--

22:05.125 --> 22:09.458
He threw it all away for a party.

22:10.625 --> 22:13.166
[voice breaking] I love my son
more than I love myself,

22:13.250 --> 22:14.750
and I want him to be OK.

22:14.834 --> 22:16.208
[crying] But I am so mad.

22:17.834 --> 22:19.792
I don't know how I'll even
be able to look at him.

22:24.750 --> 22:26.291
[Owen] Schmitt,
check on her post-op H&amp;H

22:26.375 --> 22:28.667
and keep an eye on her urine output, OK?

22:32.917 --> 22:33.875
Owen...

22:34.875 --> 22:36.083
what's going on?

22:37.542 --> 22:39.166
What's wrong? I-- [sighs]

22:40.583 --> 22:41.667
What are you not saying? I know you.

22:41.750 --> 22:44.166
I-I know that there is something wrong.

22:46.667 --> 22:48.834
Do you think maybe
you're projecting, Teddy?

22:48.917 --> 22:51.291
I mean [chuckles] what are <i>you </i>not saying?

22:51.375 --> 22:52.709
What are you not telling <i>me?</i>

22:54.458 --> 22:55.583
I'm right here.

22:57.417 --> 22:59.542
I'm right here, Teddy, and I love you.

23:00.917 --> 23:03.792
And I [sighs] I trust you.

23:05.417 --> 23:07.166
And you're my best friend.

23:07.250 --> 23:08.667
So if there's something...

23:10.250 --> 23:14.291
you need to tell me, now is the time.

23:18.709 --> 23:21.208
No. No, there--
there's nothing. [chuckles]

23:21.917 --> 23:22.750
Nothing.

23:23.375 --> 23:26.208
[inhales deeply]

23:26.291 --> 23:27.542
[sighs]

23:29.959 --> 23:33.667
[Teddy and Koracick moaning]

23:33.750 --> 23:36.000
[Teddy] <i>Oh, God. Oh.</i>

23:36.083 --> 23:37.750
[Koracick]
<i>Let's not wait till 7:00. Let's leave now.</i>

23:37.834 --> 23:40.000
[Teddy] <i>No, I can't. </i>[breathing heavily]

23:40.083 --> 23:41.417
-Schmitt--
-[Teddy] <i>I can't leave with you.</i>

23:41.500 --> 23:44.250
-Oh, my God.
-Schmitt played this for me in the OR.

23:44.333 --> 23:45.917
<i>-I am marrying Owen.</i>
-...on what was supposed to be

23:46.000 --> 23:46.959
our wedding day.

23:47.792 --> 23:48.959
[sighs]

23:50.875 --> 23:52.083
So much for love.

23:54.834 --> 23:56.500
So much for friendship.

23:56.583 --> 23:58.208
So much for-- [sniffles]

23:58.750 --> 24:00.875
So much for trust. [chuckles dryly]

24:02.125 --> 24:03.375
-Owen, I--
-So much for us.

24:03.458 --> 24:04.417
-Owen, wait, wait.
-No.

24:04.500 --> 24:06.083
Oh, my God. Wait. Owen.

24:06.166 --> 24:08.542
Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

24:08.625 --> 24:10.583
[crying]

24:10.667 --> 24:12.083
Oh, my God.

24:18.125 --> 24:20.667
No. They said he was <i>out </i>of surgery.

24:21.375 --> 24:23.208
There were some complications.

24:23.291 --> 24:26.291
Uh, y-your son's burns were much
deeper than we saw initially,

24:26.375 --> 24:28.375
so they had to take him back in.

24:29.125 --> 24:29.959
Sorry.

24:32.000 --> 24:33.750
Kayden told me about the party

24:33.834 --> 24:35.166
and asked if he could take the car.

24:36.750 --> 24:39.625
And I had this feeling in my gut
like it's not a good idea.

24:40.834 --> 24:41.792
But I figured,

24:43.041 --> 24:44.667
it's just a few kids.

24:44.750 --> 24:45.959
They'll all wear masks.

24:47.583 --> 24:48.709
No one will find out.

24:49.625 --> 24:51.875
[GoldFord's "Walk With Me" playing]

24:51.959 --> 24:53.583
Why didn't I say no?

24:57.333 --> 25:01.834
<i>♪ Walk with me, I'll walk with you ♪</i>

25:03.750 --> 25:09.542
<i>♪ Down these troubled roads</i>
<i>We've stumbled into ♪</i>

25:10.000 --> 25:12.959
<i>♪ We're all in this thing together ♪</i>

25:13.041 --> 25:15.542
<i>♪ We're gonna make it through ♪</i>

25:15.625 --> 25:20.667
<i>♪ Walk with me, I'll walk with you ♪</i>

25:21.250 --> 25:26.625
<i>♪ Be there for me, I'll be there for you ♪</i>

25:28.125 --> 25:31.083
<i>♪ When we're running out of hope ♪</i>

25:31.166 --> 25:34.083
<i>♪ When we don't know what to do ♪</i>

25:34.166 --> 25:39.625
<i>♪ Like a candle in the darkness</i>
<i>Shining bright and true ♪</i>

25:39.834 --> 25:45.500
<i>♪ Be there for me, I'll be there for you ♪</i>

25:45.875 --> 25:50.542
<i>♪ Walk with me, I'll walk with you ♪</i>

25:50.625 --> 25:51.917
[cellphone vibrates, chimes]

25:52.000 --> 25:54.875
<i>♪ I know the rain of today ♪</i>

25:54.959 --> 25:58.166
<i>♪ Will bring tomorrow's bloom ♪</i>

25:58.250 --> 26:01.000
<i>♪ When we can't see where we're goin' ♪</i>

26:01.083 --> 26:03.500
<i>♪ Or what the world is coming to ♪</i>

26:03.583 --> 26:09.041
<i>♪ Will you walk with me?</i>
<i>Oh, I'll walk with you ♪</i>

26:14.041 --> 26:16.375
<i>♪ Walk with me ♪</i>

26:19.041 --> 26:22.458
<i>♪ And I will walk with you ♪</i>

26:26.000 --> 26:28.834
<i>♪ Walk with me ♪</i>

26:31.083 --> 26:34.125
<i>♪ And I will walk with you ♪</i>

26:34.208 --> 26:36.375
<i>♪ It's gonna be ♪</i>

26:36.458 --> 26:38.041
<i>♪ Oh, it's gonna be ♪</i>

26:38.125 --> 26:41.375
<i>-♪ Walk with me ♪</i>
<i>-♪ Gonna be, gonna be all right ♪</i>

26:41.458 --> 26:42.917
<i>♪ Everything ♪</i>

26:43.083 --> 26:46.250
<i>-♪ And I will walk with you ♪</i>
<i>-♪ Is gonna be all right ♪</i>

